State
Event
Intent
View (Compose): The view layer is the interface of the app. These are
passive elements responsible for displaying a state and receiving
intents (aka actions).
State Holder (ViewModels): These components are responsible for
holding the state of the view. They act as a coordinator between the
view and the model.
Intent: The Intent is usually mapped to a user interaction. Eg. When a
user clicks on a button.
Event: The Event is a one shot side effect. An event is usually "fire
and forget", an example is a navigation event.
State: The State is all the information necessary for the app to be
useful. It holds the current screen state, for example if the data is
loading, but also other information, that might not be directly
representative in the UI.
Domain
Use cases
Entities
Repositories
(interfaces)
Use cases: Use cases are essentially what hold the business logic of the
app. Depending on the case, they might be redundant. Generally, these
provide a way to have testable, reusable, and consistent business logic
across the app. On the downside, there is some code overhead.
Entities: These are the core data structures of the app and are directly
representative of the business requirements.
Repositories interfaces: These are the contracts telling the rest of the
app how to receive information from the outside world.
Data
Data Transfer
Objects (DTOs)
Repositories
(implementations)
Database
Data Sources
Remote (Http)
Data Sources: These components set up any work required to communicate
with the outside world. For example, a remote datasource, would use anhttp
client to make http requests, receive and serialize http responses.
Data Transfer Objects (DTOs): These are usually very similar to the Domain
Entities. Their job is to provide a serializable object, such that it can be
easily sent through different channels. These objects tend to be quite "dirty"
as not everyone upholds the contracts set by the business.
Repositories implementation: These are the actual repositories as explained
from the domain. By using data sources, their job is to transform and/or hold
data coming in and out of the app.
